============================================================
RESULTS & ANALYTICAL INSIGHTS
Python Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
============================================================

Description:
This section presents the main analytical insights obtained
through the Python Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) phase of
the project.

Using the structured datasets generated from the SQL module,
the analysis transforms aggregated football statistics into
visual and interpretable insights through charts, scatter
plots, and heatmaps.

The objective is not only to visualize the dataset, but also
to identify meaningful patterns related to:
- team performance
- scoring behavior
- competitive balance
- home advantage
- rivalry dynamics
- offensive and defensive efficiency


------------------------------------------------------------
General Dataset Analysis
------------------------------------------------------------

The general overview confirms several important characteristics
of the Premier League dataset.

The league demonstrates a relatively high-scoring profile,
with more than 11,000 total goals and an average close to
2.7 goals per match. Most matches contain fewer than three
goals, while high-scoring games remain less common.

The analysis also confirms the existence of a clear
home-field advantage, as home wins occur significantly more
frequently than away wins.

Discipline-related metrics reveal that yellow cards are
consistently present across matches, while red cards remain
rare events, reflecting realistic football match behavior.


------------------------------------------------------------
Team Performance Analysis
------------------------------------------------------------

Team-level analysis highlights strong differences in
performance between clubs.

Teams such as Manchester City, Liverpool, Manchester United,
and Chelsea consistently dominate across most metrics,
including:
- total wins
- win rate
- average goals scored
- goal difference

Manchester City stands out as the strongest overall team,
combining:
- high attacking production
- strong defensive performance
- exceptional win efficiency

Scatter plot analysis demonstrates a clear relationship
between offensive strength, defensive stability, and overall
success. Teams that score more goals while conceding fewer
consistently achieve higher win rates and stronger goal
differences.

Correlation heatmaps further confirm that:
- goal difference strongly correlates with win rate
- successful teams tend to maintain balanced attacking and
  defensive profiles
- strong teams perform consistently both home and away

The analysis also reinforces the importance of home advantage,
with most clubs showing noticeably better performance in
home matches compared to away fixtures.


------------------------------------------------------------
Big 5 Matchup Analysis
------------------------------------------------------------

The matchup analysis focuses on direct rivalries between
elite Premier League clubs:
- Arsenal
- Manchester City
- Manchester United
- Chelsea
- Liverpool

The results reveal that different rivalries exhibit distinct
playing styles and competitive characteristics.

Some matchups, such as Arsenal vs Liverpool and Liverpool vs
Manchester City, consistently produce high-scoring games,
reflecting open and attacking football.

Other rivalries display increased physical intensity,
characterized by higher numbers of fouls and disciplinary
actions.

Dominance analysis also shows that while certain matchups
remain highly balanced across seasons, others demonstrate
clear long-term superiority by one team.

Heatmap visualizations provide a broader understanding of
match behavior by comparing goals, shots, fouls, and corners
across different rivalries.


------------------------------------------------------------
Overall Conclusion
------------------------------------------------------------

The Python EDA phase successfully transforms structured SQL
outputs into meaningful football analytics insights.

The analysis demonstrates how visualization techniques can
be used to:
- understand team behavior
- identify competitive patterns
- evaluate offensive and defensive efficiency
- analyze rivalry dynamics
- support deeper statistical exploration

Overall, the results establish a complete analytical
workflow that combines:
- SQL-based data preparation
- Python visualization
- statistical interpretation
- structured sports analytics

These insights also create a strong foundation for the next
stage of the project, where the structured datasets can be
extended into Machine Learning and predictive modeling
applications.